    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-02-20T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-02-20T10:00:00-05:00" n="613"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d613">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/8561: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fish</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-20T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >February 20, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 23—8:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>82. Foreign Minister Eden<note n="23" xml:id="d613fn23">Anthony Eden, British
                        Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs.</note> and General Dill<note n="24"
                        xml:id="d613fn24">Gen. Sir John Dill, Chief of the Imperial General
                        Staff.</note> arrived at Cairo last night by air. Donovan, who had delayed
                    his departure at the request of the British in order to meet them, tells me that
                    he talked with them and General Wavell last night and was informed that all
                    three intend proceeding to Turkey and Greece in an attempt to work out a joint
                    effort in the Balkans. Donovan states that he submitted his appraisal of the
                    strategic situation in this area (see my telegram No. 81, February 20, 3
                        p.m.<note n="25" xml:id="d613fn25">Not printed.</note>) to them and that
                    they and Wavell concurred <pb facs="0660" n="648" xml:id="pg_648"/> in his
                    conclusions and stressed particularly the necessity of airplanes and mechanized
                    equipment to make any effort effective.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Fish</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
